title: "Magic" Energies For Detecting Light Elements With Resonant Alpha Particle Backscattering

x4freetext: "Magic" Energies For Detecting Light Elements With
Resonant Alpha Particle Backscattering

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Los Alamos Scientific Lab. Reports, No.98-4867 (1998)

x4codes.hlp: Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America
Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America

x4freetext: BP
A polystyrene layer 8000 A thick spun onto a silicon
substrate was used for the hydrogen elastic recoil
cross section measurement.
The hydrogen recoil cross sections were measured at
scattering angle of 30 degrees with a target tilt of
75 degrees. The cross section in the energy region of
interest was obtained by first measuring the yield
from the sample at 2.5 MeV, where the cross section
is known. At both high and low energies the target
was thin enough that the yield could be determined by
peak integration. This removes the uncertainties
associated with stopping cross sections. The yield
obtained in the region of 5-6 MeV was then scaled by
the 2.5 MeV cross section to determine the cross
section.
The uncertainty in the elastic recoil ratios
is 6%.
The hydrogen cross section was corrected for hydrogen
loss.
Fig. 1.

x4freetext: The boron sample was deposited on a 5 mm thick carbon
substrate. The boron in the sample was separated from
the substrate by a 4000 A layer of Mo. This separates,
in energy, the boron signal from the carbon
substrate signal. The boron layer was a
sputter-coated layer of B4C, 500 A thick.
A standard procedure for measuring backscattering
cross sections is the ratio method. The ratio method
can be derived from the equation for the experimental
cross section for a given element sigma = Y / Q(Nt)
deltaOmega, where sigma is the cross section, Y is the
integrated yield, Q is the number of incident
particles, (Nt) is the atoms/cm2 in the target and
deltaOmega is the solid angle of the detector. While
Y can be measured to arbitrarily good statistical
uncertainty, the other parameters have higher
systematic uncertainties.
The statistical uncertainties in the
backscattering ratio measurements are 4%.
Fig. 1.

x4freetext: The boron sample was deposited on a 5 mm thick carbon
substrate. The boron in the sample was separated from
the substrate by a 4000 A layer of Mo. This separates,
in energy, the boron signal from the carbon
substrate signal. The boron layer was a
sputter-coated layer of B4C, 500 A thick.
A standard procedure for measuring backscattering
cross sections is the ratio method. The ratio method
can be derived from the equation for the experimental
cross section for a given element sigma = Y / Q(Nt)
deltaOmega, where sigma is the cross section, Y is the
integrated yield, Q is the number of incident
particles, (Nt) is the atoms/cm2 in the target and
deltaOmega is the solid angle of the detector. While
Y can be measured to arbitrarily good statistical
uncertainty, the other parameters have higher
systematic uncertainties.
Choosing the analysis energy in this region depends
on the elements expected in the sample. If boron is
present in a relatively thin film, the best energy is
= 5.625 MeV. At this energy silicon has relatively
few resonances in the region of the light element
signals and can be used as a substrate material.
Table 1.
